      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Observations\n\n- **K-type constants** dominate the database, accounting for over three-quarters of all entries. These represent stepwise equilibrium constants for successive ligand binding (e.g., ML, ML₂, ML₃…).\n- **H-type constants** (≈12%) capture protonation or hydrolysis equilibria, which are essential for understanding speciation in aqueous systems at varying pH.\n- **S-type constants** (≈11%) represent cumulative (overall) stability constants (β values), which describe the formation of a complex directly from the free metal and ligands in a single expression.\n\nThe heavy weighting toward stepwise constants reflects the experimental tradition in coordination chemistry, where successive formation constants are typically measured and reported individually rather than as cumulative products.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
